'It means a lot,'  Mr Below said, but added  
'The real heroes are the ones that are engraved on the Vietnam wall ... 
the real heroes are our POWs.

'This is just a little bit of me trying to 
help my country for my fellow people. Your freedom is not free,' he told the Courier Press.

The terrifying event unfolded on  March 20, 1968 when Mr Below was transporting a truck of  artillery gun tubes between Pleiko and Da Nang in Vietnam.

The vehicle in front set off a delayed landmine and Mr Below and his co-driver were blown up as the truck careered off the road.

